  "local_port": 50726,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why don't install a battery for desktop computer?",
  "response": "Installing a battery in a desktop computer isn't a common practice for several reasons:\n\n1. **Power Supply Design**: Desktop computers are designed to be powered by a constant mains electricity supply via a power outlet. Their power supply units (PSUs) convert AC from the wall outlet to the various DC voltages required by internal components. Unlike laptops, desktops don't usually have built-in mechanisms for battery power management.\n\n2. **Size and Efficiency**: Batteries large enough to power a desktop computer would be bulky and inefficient. Desktops tend to consume more power due to more robust components like high-performance CPUs and GPUs. A battery capable of supporting this load would be impractically large and heavy.\n\n3. **Cost**: Adding a battery to a desktop system would significantly increase the cost. The battery itself would be expensive, along with the necessary circuitry for charging and power management.\n\n4. **Heat and Space**: Desktop computers generally run at higher power levels than laptops, creating more heat that needs to be managed. Adding a battery could exacerbate cooling challenges and require additional space in the case design.\n\n5. **UPS as a Solution**: For power backup solutions, an uninterruptible power supply (UPS) is typically used with desktop computers. UPS devices can provide temporary power in case of an outage, giving users enough time to save their work and properly shut down their computer. They are external devices, which makes them easier to manage.\n\nBy relying on external solutions like UPS units, desktop computers can maintain their performance and design advantages without the need for an internal battery system.",
